/* C:\Users\Edwin Boston\OneDrive\Desktop\III\STDLIB\iii\omnia\tp_dispatch_consts.iii
 *
 * III STDLIB - omnia::tp_dispatch_consts -- FROZEN-SPEC transform-codec
 * and codegen-dispatch slot-ID constants.
 *
 * These are NOT a removable codegen workaround.  Each constant is an
 * opaque u64 ID equal to the slot index in the canonical 24-codec
 * registration order (FROZEN SPEC §7B.6) / the codegen-dispatch order
 * (FROZEN SPEC §7C / §Z.C.7).  They are consumed by \`when kind { ... }\`
 * cascades per the hardcoded-dynamism discipline (§46) -- deliberately
 * integer IDs, not function pointers.  transform_patterns.iii uses
 * e.g. \`cg_dispatch_default\` as the ID 40, never as a fn-address; the
 * actual codec/dispatch implementations live in their per-module files.
 * Removing or "de-workaround-ing" these would violate the frozen spec
 * and the §46 discipline.
 *
 * Linker-discipline note (true, secondary): const symbols emit
 * \`L_<NAME>\`, function symbols emit \`<name>\` (post Phase XII-ξ,
 * extern/@export fn-address-takes also emit raw \`<name>\`), so a const
 * and a fn sharing a name do not collide at link time even though iii
 * grammar would forbid same-module shadowing.  This is an observation
 * about the layout, not the reason the module exists.
 *
 * Hexad: kind_compose.  Ring: R3.  K: 0.95.
 */

